nter of\ntown, near east\nBide\n.quick.\nm:\nStoreBP5\nJ&JW blocks from STETSON\u2014novelties designed by HA\nWES\nmaker of America's\" best $3.0() hats\u2014Quality is the main\nspring that pushes our business forward.\nHX STBDOOIiED\nhe is prepared to\nturn out just as fine work as can be\ndone anywhere on earth. This en\nterprising firm h&s been compelled\nto rent larger quarters, and are now\nin their new shop at 112 W. ltemj\u00a3''\nThey are ready with the goods, and\nask for a liberal share of patronage.\nnerved\nschool house.\nWill sell this property for $1300, on\nthe following easy termajWOO down,\nbalance on time. The house rents\nfor $7 per month. To anyone look\ning for nn investment this cannot\nbe beaten. Apply at\nthis\noffice.^Ct\n\u2022\u2022t-rir t.\\'\u201e\nof a :.Hundred Hat Styles\n\u2022-Wtisw\n11\n/'liu\nHUPPED LIKE I BAT\nLooked In the!\nSinking Ship,\nWEjNT DOWN\nof\nAS HE SLEPT*\nAwok. to Find Water Pouring InUpen\nHim and Every Avenue of Eso\u00abpe\nCut Off\u2014Tide Turned In the Nick of\nImprisoned in the cabin of a sinking\n*\u2022\u2022\u20221, Trtth:tl\u00bb water rapidly rising\nabout him, Harry Willey, mats of the\nHull..(England) steam trawler Quail,\n\u2022scaped death by a miraculous Inter\nvention of the -fates. His experience\nwould have whitened the hair and un\nbalanced the mind of a less hardy\nman. Like a rat In a submerged trap,\nhe swam about until, standing on tip\ntoe on a table, he was able to raise his\nnose and mouth above the water Into\nthe few inches of breathmg space that\n\u2022till remained in the skylight Finally\nafter an hour of effort, when he was\nabout to abandon the fight and resign\nhimself to the Inevitable, the water\nbegan receding with the ebbing tide,\nand in a short time he was able tc\nforce the cabin door and reach the tip\nper deck. The boat had sunk in shal\nlow water.\nThe Quail was run down In the\nHumber by the Wilson Uher Dynamc\nwhile Wlfley and the rest of the Crew\nwere asleep In the cabin. With the\nexception of the mate, the men were\nable to escape and were taken off later\nby the boats of the Dynamo. Willey\nawoke, however, to find the watei\nrushing into the cabin through the\nwindows. He jumped out' of his bunk\nand made for the door as fast as he\ncould, but the water, which already\nfilled the cabin up to Willey's waist,\nheld It tight He struggled fiercely,\ndesperately, to pull It open, but hi\nvain. The rapidly rising water drove\nhim from It It was now: about his\nshoulders, and, groping In the dark, he\nfinally with his feet located, the table\nunder the skylight Mounting It,, he at\ntempted to force the skylight, his last\nhope.. It stuck even more securely than\nthe door.\nThe water rose rapidly about the Im\nprisoned man\u2014to his knees, to his hips.\nFUBCEM, BUT Of VAIN.\nto his shoulders\u2014and finally be was\ncompelled to stuad on tiptoe to utilize\nthe small 6pace that still remained In\nthe skylight Two Inches more of wa\nter and It would be all over.\nSuddenly he heard blows struck on\nthe top of the skylight and he rightly\nsurmised that his shipmates were try\ning to force the top In the hope that he\nwas still alive. It stoutly resisted their\nassault 'however, and they finally\nabandoned the effort, thinking that the\nman Inside was dead.\nWorn out\nby\nhis efforts and\nby\nun-:\nthe sound of the retreating\nfootstepB of his companions, Willey\nBlipped\nfrom the\ntable\nand went under.\nWith a great effort however, he suc\nceeded In holding to\na\nledge and\npull\u00ad\ning his head above water In the sky\nlight again. But the hold was a preca\nrious and difficult one, and he\nknow-\nthat he could not last long. Just as be\nwas about to give up hope he noticed\nthat the water was slowly receding.\nAt first he did not believe his senses,\nbut as ho watched the shifting mark\nof the water on the side of the\nsky\u00ad\nlight his first Impression was con\nfirmed. After a titae which to the ex\nhausted man seemed almost an eter\nnity he was able to. abandon his ua-\nBright, snappy colors are the strongest features of this\nspring's^hat offering. We show more shades and shapes than\neasyperch andiry^e 4o6i. agab^It\nyielded to hl#,efforts, and as it swung\n*pen the rush of wateSr cartifed tilm off\nhia feet and landed hbfirjn safety\nthe deck. He lay there exhausted^\ntU the crew of the Dynamo saw\naad came to his rescue.,\nOWES LIFE TO WlS\" 000.\nMongrel Cur. Rescues Butoher\nprisoned In Jeebox},u\nThe intelligence of a moiuprel dog\nand the ready aid of a policeman saved\nAntonio fetrucelll of -Bast Oae Hun\ndred and Forty-eighth street, New*\nYork city, a young butcher, from bleed\ning to death while he was a prisoner\ntn his employer's Icebox at 584 Morris\navenue, the Bronx.\nThe young mon went Into the ice\nbox with a big sharp knife and in try\ning to keep the dqor rom closing slip\nped and fell on the knife. The sharp\nblade cut an artery in his right thigh.'\nTHE BOO BUSKED CP TO THE DrfOB OP THB\nICEBOX.\nHe gave one loud' groan and became\nunconscious as the door slammed, im\nprisoning him. -v\nThere/was no one in Nicola Boucco's\nshop at the time. But Dick, the dog,\nwhom the butcher's assistant had been\nfeeding, realized that his Mend was\nIn trouble. Dick ran up the avenue\nbarking and at the cornet' circled\naround Policeman Wlckman and De\ntective John O'Brien until he got the\nofficers'attention.\nDick then led the way to the shop,\nbarking and looking back constantly.\nThe dog rushed up to the door of the\nicebox and howled. When Wi?kmah\nopened the door Petrucelll was near\nfleath.\ni-f\nsr-tri\nAn Artist.\nPRiVATE\nBOARDING\n\"Coming out with flying colors.\"\n\u2014New York World.\nLength and Breadth.\n\"What would you charge to paint\nmy portrait full length7*-'\n\"Do yon want It full width too7\u2014\nHarper's. Weekly.\nlatns\nAiburyPariu\n$l**gyman\nLI oka Wei\nBells PUl\ngroohi, and Wedding\nRing\u2014One Bid\u00bbd C|0:\nParent** Weapprovef\nDriven to the altar\nMiss Belle,CTousej the pretty*youl\ndaughter of Rev. N. P. Crowe, pasto\nof the First Presbyterian tshurch ei\nStanhope, N. J., broke down In th\nmidst of a marriage cerean&y\nin another moment would haw\nher the ^ife of Percy. BisselL\nThrowing herself upon ^officiating\nclergyman, Rev. Dr 0. M. Griffin, pas?!\ntor of the First Methodist church oi\nAsbury Park, N. J, she cried hysteric^\nally how her lover had forced her\nthe altar at the point of a revolver.\nInstantly there was a lively mixup,\nl)r. Griffin clinchlhg with the aaltorJwj\nthrowing him to the floor and btndiqiM\nhis arms. Then be took his revolvef\naway and, standing guard over the\nprostrate form bf y6ung Bisbell, sen\nMiss Crouse for a policeman.' Instead:^|l?\nshe rushed to a cottage In Ocean\nma oxibboxuak -oxraoaaD\nGrovtrJ4*'\"\nwhere she was stopping with her par\u00ae\u00ae\u00bb.\n\u2022lata.\nLater Blssell broke away from the\nMethodist parsonage, where the cere\nmony had been going on, and again\nforced his attentions^ on Miss Crouse,\nthough in order to do so be had to\nbreak through a window of the Ocean\nGrove house.\nAt this stage of the proceedings\npoliceman intervened and, taking Bls\nsell to the station, started htm off on\na train for New York. Tlfe Crouse\nfamily refused to moke charges against\nhim and pleaded that the fracas be\nhushed up.\nGreat efforts were made to keep thej\naffair from the public. The prtncl]\nhave enjoyed a high sociitl standing\nStanhope. Miss Crouse, daughter\nthe Presbyterian pastor, is-exceeding]\npretty and, is a social favorite In tbg|^\ntown. She^ recently graduated frouJS%\nBlair Hall.\nBlssell is the son of prominoat resi\ndents of Stanhope and Until recently\nsang in the Presbyterian church cholrf\nHe Is a teacher In the Sunday school\nof the church and student at the\nTrenton State Normal school.\nObjection to his attentions had late$.^.\nIy been made by Bev. and Mrs. Crous^*\"'\nThe Grouses had taken their daughteTv^\nto Ocean Grove that she inlght avoid\nhim. Kev. Mr. Grouse told his daugh^\ntor of rumors about BisseU's life onty\nrecently, and she lmtnedlately wrote i\"\nBUIXOB.\nhim a letter at the Normal schooi la\nTrenton refusing to have anything\nfurther to do with him, and a few\ndays ago the Rev. Mr. and Mrs. Crouse\nand their daughter went'to Ocean\nGrove for a short rest staying at 78,\nIiake avenue.\n/a- w-\nUpon receipt of Miss Grouse's lettwti\nyoung Blssell left Trenton and went\nStanhope. Finding toe parsoi\nclosed, he went to Ocean Grove. Miss\nGrouse met Blssell on the street as he~\nwas searching for her. He was great--\nly excited and demoded ^hat she marH\ntr him lmmiediately. Miss Crouse flat-.\nly refused and begjpd him to leave thei-''\ntows.\n'i\nMiss Crouse says she pleaded witb^i\nhim Marly two houra. Finally Blssell^,\nas they walked along the ocean fronfc\nin the dusk, declared if she refused to\nmarry him he would shoot her and\"\"\nthen himself. Miss Grouse, thorough^/\nly scared, consented to go to Rev.\nM. Griffin, whom she knew, and be^v/\nm\u00bbrried.\nHer plan, she says, was to get Bls\nsell somewhere where she cocild\ntain assistance ijnd protection.~~CaL,\nlog a hackman, Cbe couple were driven\"!\n,to the parsonage of tin Ilwt Metho-^x\n4ist Episcopal church, and J?\". GrlfHa-\"\nas asked to marry them. Then she\n\u2022I\n*b\n'I","height":"25864","width":"18216"}}
